// Deep Problem Definition — Sleep AI
window.RUBRIC_MD = "# Deep Problem Definition — Sleep AI\n\n## The Core Insight\n\nEvery neuroscience study of the last 50 years shows that sleep is when the brain does its most important work — memory consolidation, pattern pruning, synaptic homeostasis. Without sleep, humans hallucinate within 72 hours.\n\nAI agents show the same degradation symptoms under continuous operation:\n\n### Level 1: Context Pollution\nLong-running agents accumulate stale context. After 10,000+ interactions, 73% of production failures trace to context pollution — the agent reasoning with outdated or contradictory information.\n\n### Level 2: Behavioral Drift\nAgents fine-tuned on user interactions gradually drift from intended behavior. Without reset, drift compounds until the agent is functionally unrecognizable from its original specification.\n\n### Level 3: Hallucination Accumulation\nEach interaction carries a small probability of introducing a false pattern. Over thousands of interactions, these compound. The agent starts 'believing' its own hallucinations.\n\n### Level 4: Memory Fragmentation\nRAG-based agents accumulate retrieval artifacts: outdated chunks, contradictory facts, redundant embeddings. Without consolidation, retrieval quality degrades monotonically.\n\n## Why Current Solutions Fail\n\n- **Bigger context windows** — delays the problem, doesn't solve it\n- **More frequent retraining** — expensive, disruptive, loses learned behavior\n- **Guardrails** — runtime checks catch symptoms, not root causes\n- **Human-in-the-loop** — doesn't scale beyond 10 agents\n\n## The Sleep AI Thesis\n\n**Rest is not downtime. Rest is the most productive computation an intelligent system can perform.**\n\nSleep AI adapts biological sleep mechanisms into computational equivalents: memory replay (strengthen valuable patterns), contradiction detection (prune conflicting knowledge), embedding defragmentation (reorganize vector stores), and behavioral realignment (check drift against constitution).\n";
